# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: voxel-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:voxel-modeling/3d-modeling] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] In 3D computer graphics and CAD, CSG is often used in procedural modeling.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] CSG can also be performed on polygonal meshes, and may or may not be procedural and/or parametric.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] CSG can be contrasted with polygon mesh modeling, boundary representation, and box modeling.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] The simplest solid objects used for the representation are called *geometric primitives*.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Typically they are the objects of simple shape: cuboids, cylinders, prisms, pyramids, spheres, cones.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] The set of allowable primitives is limited by each software package.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Some software packages allow CSG on curved objects while other packages do not.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] An object is *constructed* from primitives by means of allowable *operations*, which are typically Boolean operations on sets: union (OR), intersection (AND) and difference (NOT), as well as geometric transformations of those sets.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] A primitive can typically be described by a procedure which accepts some number of parameters; for example, a sphere may be described by the coordinates of its center point, along with a radius value.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Combining these elementary operations, it is possible to build up objects with high complexity starting from simple ones.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Rendering of constructive solid geometry is particularly simple when ray tracing.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Ray tracers intersect a ray with both primitives that are being operated on, apply the operator to the intersection intervals along the 1D ray, and then take the point closest to the camera along the ray as being the result.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Constructive solid geometry has a number of practical uses.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] It is used in cases where simple geometric objects are desired, or where mathematical accuracy is important.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Nearly all engineering CAD packages use CSG (where it may be useful for representing tool cuts, and features where parts must fit together).
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] The *Quake* engine and Unreal Engine both use this system, as does Hammer (the native Source engine level editor), and Torque Game Engine/Torque Game Engine Advanced.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] CSG is popular because a modeler can use a set of relatively simple objects to create very complicated geometry.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] When CSG is procedural or parametric, the user can revise their complex geometry by changing the position of objects or by changing the Boolean operation used to combine those objects.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] One of the advantages of CSG is that it can easily assure that objects are "solid" or water-tight if all of the primitive shapes are water-tight.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] This can be important for some manufacturing or engineering computation applications.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] By comparison, when creating geometry based upon boundary representations, additional topological data is required, or consistency checks must be performed to assure that the given boundary description specifies a valid solid object.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] A convenient property of CSG shapes is that it is easy to classify arbitrary points as being either inside or outside the shape created by CSG.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] The point is simply classified against all the underlying primitives and the resulting Boolean expression is evaluated.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] This is a desirable quality for some applications such as ray tracing.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] With CSG models being parameterized by construction, they are often favorable over usual meshes when it comes to applications where the goal is to fabricate customized models.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] For such applications it can be interesting to convert already existing meshes to CSG trees.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] This problem of automatically converting meshes to CSG trees is called **inverse CSG**.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] A resulting CSG tree is required to occupy the same volume in 3D space as the input mesh while having a minimal number of nodes.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Simple solutions are preferred to ensure that the resulting model is easy to edit.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Solving this problem is a challenge because of the large search space that has to be explored.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] It combines continuous parameters such as dimension and size of the primitive shapes, and discrete parameters such as the Boolean operators used to build the final CSG tree.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Deductive methods solve this problem by building a set of half-spaces that describe the interior of the geometry.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] These half-spaces are used to describe primitives that can be combined to get the final model.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] Another approach decouples the detection of primitive shapes and the computation of the CSG tree that defines the final model.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] This approach exploits the ability of modern program synthesis tools to find a CSG tree with minimal complexity.
[src:voxel-modeling/constructive-solid-geometry] There are also approaches that use genetic algorithms to iteratively optimize an initial shape towards the shape of the desired mesh.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] An **octree** is a tree data structure in which each internal node has exactly eight children.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Octrees are most often used to partition a three-dimensional space by recursively subdividing it into eight octants.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Octrees are the three-dimensional analog of quadtrees.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The word is derived from *oct* (Greek root meaning "eight") + *tree*.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Octrees are often used in 3D graphics and 3D game engines.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Each node in an octree subdivides the space it represents into eight octants.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] In a point region (PR) octree (analogous to a point quadtree), the node stores an explicit three-dimensional point, which is the "center" of the subdivision for that node; the point defines one of the corners for each of the eight children.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] In a matrix-based (MX) octree (analogous to a region quadtree), the subdivision point is implicitly the center of the space the node represents.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The root node of a PR octree can represent infinite space; the root node of an MX octree must represent a finite bounded space so that the implicit centers are well-defined.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Note that octrees are not the same as *k*-d trees: *k*-d trees split along a dimension and octrees split around a point.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Also *k*-d trees are always binary, which is not the case for octrees.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] By using a depth-first search the nodes are to be traversed and only required surfaces are to be viewed.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] A spatial subdivision much like an octree was used in 1934, in the Whitney covering lemma in mathematics.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The octree color quantization algorithm, invented by Gervautz and Purgathofer in 1988, encodes image color data as an octree up to nine levels deep.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Octrees are used because $2^{3}=8$ and there are three color components in the RGB system.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The node index to branch out from at the top level is determined by a formula that uses the most significant bits of the red, green, and blue color components, e.g.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The next lower level uses the next bit significance, and so on.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Less significant bits are sometimes ignored to reduce the tree size.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The algorithm is highly memory efficient because the tree's size can be limited.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The bottom level of the octree consists of leaf nodes that accrue color data not represented in the tree; these nodes initially contain single bits.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] If much more than the desired number of palette colors are entered into the octree, its size can be continually reduced by seeking out a bottom-level node and averaging its bit data up into a leaf node, pruning part of the tree.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Once sampling is complete, exploring all routes in the tree down to the leaf nodes, taking note of the bits along the way, will yield approximately the required number of colors.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The example recursive algorithm outline below (MATLAB syntax) decomposes an array of 3-dimensional points into octree style bins.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The implementation begins with a single bin surrounding all given points, which then recursively subdivides into its 8 octree regions.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Recursion is stopped when a given exit condition is met.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Taking the full list of colors of a 24-bit RGB image as point input to the Octree point decomposition implementation outlined above, the following example show the results of octree color quantization.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] The first image is the original (532818 distinct colors), while the second is the quantized image (184 distinct colors) using octree decomposition, with each pixel assigned the color at the center of the octree bin in which it falls.
[src:voxel-modeling/octree] Alternatively, final colors could be chosen at the centroid of all colors in each octree bin, however this added computation has very little effect on the visual result.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] In mathematics, a **volume element** provides a means for integrating a function with respect to volume in various coordinate systems such as spherical coordinates and cylindrical coordinates.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] The notion of a volume element is not limited to three dimensions: in two dimensions it is often known as the **area element**, and in this setting it is useful for doing surface integrals.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Under changes of coordinates, the volume element changes by the absolute value of the Jacobian determinant of the coordinate transformation (by the change of variables formula).
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] This fact allows volume elements to be defined as a kind of measure on a manifold.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] On an orientable differentiable manifold, a volume element typically arises from a volume form: a top degree differential form.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] On a non-orientable manifold, the volume element is typically the absolute value of a (locally defined) volume form: it defines a 1-density.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] On an *oriented* Riemannian manifold of dimension *n*, the volume element is a volume form equal to the Hodge dual of the unit constant function, $f(x)=1$ : $\omega =\star 1.$ Equivalently, the volume element is precisely the Levi-Civita tensor $\epsilon$ .
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] In coordinates, $\omega =\epsilon ={\sqrt {\left|\det g\right|}}\,\mathrm {d} x^{1}\wedge \cdots \wedge \mathrm {d} x^{n}$ where $\det g$ is the determinant of the metric tensor *g* written in the coordinate system.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] A simple example of a volume element can be explored by considering a two-dimensional surface embedded in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Such a volume element is sometimes called an *area element*.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Consider a subset $U\subset \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ and a mapping function $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ thus defining a surface embedded in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] In two dimensions, volume is just area, and a volume element gives a way to determine the area of parts of the surface.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Here we will find the volume element on the surface that defines area in the usual sense.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] The Jacobian matrix of the mapping is $J_{ij}={\frac {\partial \varphi _{i}}{\partial u_{j}}}$ with index *i* running from 1 to *n*, and *j* running from 1 to 2.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] For a regular surface, this determinant is non-vanishing; equivalently, the Jacobian matrix has rank 2.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Given the above construction, it should now be straightforward to understand how the volume element is invariant under an orientation-preserving change of coordinates.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] In two dimensions, the volume is just the area.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Thus, in either coordinate system, the volume element takes the same expression: the expression of the volume element is invariant under a change of coordinates.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] Note that there was nothing particular to two dimensions in the above presentation; the above trivially generalizes to arbitrary dimensions.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-element] For example, consider the sphere with radius *r* centered at the origin in **R**3.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] In scientific visualization and computer graphics, **volume rendering** is a set of techniques used to display a 2D projection of a 3D discretely sampled data set, typically a 3D scalar field.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] A typical 3D data set is a group of 2D slice images acquired by a CT, MRI, or MicroCT scanner.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Usually these are acquired in a regular pattern (e.g., one slice for each millimeter of depth) and usually have a regular number of image pixels in a regular pattern.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This is an example of a regular volumetric grid, with each volume element, or voxel represented by a single value that is obtained by sampling the immediate area surrounding the voxel.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] To render a 2D projection of the 3D data set, one first needs to define a camera in space relative to the volume.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Also, one needs to define the opacity and color of every voxel.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This is usually defined using an RGBA (for red, green, blue, alpha) transfer function that defines the RGBA value for every possible voxel value.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] For example, a volume may be viewed by extracting isosurfaces (surfaces of equal values) from the volume and rendering them as polygonal meshes or by rendering the volume directly as a block of data.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The marching cubes algorithm is a common technique for extracting an isosurface from volume data.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Direct volume rendering is a computationally intensive task that may be performed in several ways.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Another method of volume rendering is Ray marching, a category of 3D computer graphics rendering techniques in which rays are traced step by step, subdividing each ray into smaller segments and sampling a function at each interval.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Volume rendering is distinguished from thin slice tomography presentations, and is also generally distinguished from projections of 3D models, including maximum intensity projection.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Still, technically, all volume renderings become projections when viewed on a 2-dimensional display, making the distinction between projections and volume renderings a bit vague.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Nevertheless, the epitomes of volume rendering models feature a mix of for example coloring and shading in order to create realistic and/or observable representations.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] A direct volume renderer requires every sample value to be mapped to opacity and a color.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This is done with a "transfer function" which can be a simple ramp, a piecewise linear function or an arbitrary table.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Once converted to an RGBA color model (for red, green, blue, alpha) value, the composed RGBA result is projected on the corresponding pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The way this is done depends on the rendering technique.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] A combination of these techniques is possible.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] For instance, a shear warp implementation could use texturing hardware to draw the aligned slices in the off-screen buffer.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The technique of volume ray casting can be derived directly from the rendering equation.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] It provides results of very high quality, usually considered to provide the best image quality.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Volume ray casting is classified as image based volume rendering technique, as the computation emanates from the output image, not the input volume data as is the case with object based techniques.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] In this technique, a ray is generated for each desired image pixel.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Using a simple camera model, the ray starts at the center of projection of the camera (usually the eye point) and passes through the image pixel on the imaginary image plane floating in between the camera and the volume to be rendered.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The ray is clipped by the boundaries of the volume in order to save time.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Then the ray is sampled at regular or adaptive intervals throughout the volume.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The data is interpolated at each sample point, the transfer function applied to form an RGBA sample, the sample is composited onto the accumulated RGBA of the ray, and the process repeated until the ray exits the volume.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The RGBA color is converted to an RGB color and deposited in the corresponding image pixel.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The process is repeated for every pixel on the screen to form the completed image.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This is a technique which trades quality for speed.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Here, every volume element is splatted, as Lee Westover said, like a snow ball, on to the viewing surface in back to front order.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] These splats are rendered as disks whose properties (color and transparency) vary diametrically in normal (Gaussian) manner.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Flat disks and those with other kinds of property distribution are also used depending on the application.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The shear warp approach to volume rendering was developed by Cameron and Undrill, popularized by Philippe Lacroute and Marc Levoy.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] In this technique, the viewing transformation is transformed such that the nearest face of the volume becomes axis aligned with an off-screen image data buffer with a fixed scale of voxels to pixels.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The volume is then rendered into this buffer using the far more favorable memory alignment and fixed scaling and blending factors.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Once all slices of the volume have been rendered, the buffer is then warped into the desired orientation and scaled in the displayed image.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This technique is relatively fast in software at the cost of less accurate sampling and potentially worse image quality compared to ray casting.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] There is memory overhead for storing multiple copies of the volume, for the ability to have near axis aligned volumes.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This overhead can be mitigated using run-length encoding.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Many 3D graphics systems use texture mapping to apply images, or textures, to geometric objects.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Commodity PC graphics cards are fast at texturing and can efficiently render slices of a 3D volume, with real time interaction capabilities.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Workstation GPUs are even faster, and are the basis for much of the production volume visualization used in medical imaging, oil and gas, and other markets (2007).
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] In earlier years, dedicated 3D texture mapping systems were used on graphics systems such as Silicon Graphics InfiniteReality, HP Visualize FX graphics accelerator, and others.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This technique was first described by Bill Hibbard and Dave Santek.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] These slices can either be aligned with the volume and rendered at an angle to the viewer, or aligned with the viewing plane and sampled from unaligned slices through the volume.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Graphics hardware support for 3D textures is needed for the second technique.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Volume aligned texturing produces images of reasonable quality.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The image quality degrades with coarse slice counts, though there is often a noticeable transition when the volume is rotated.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Due to the extremely parallel nature of direct volume rendering, special purpose volume rendering hardware was a rich research topic before GPU volume rendering became fast enough.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The most widely cited technology was the VolumePro real-time ray-casting system, developed by Hanspeter Pfister and scientists at Mitsubishi Electric Research Laboratories, which used high memory bandwidth and brute force to render using the ray casting algorithm.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The technology was transferred to TeraRecon, Inc. and two generations of ASICs were produced and sold.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Pixel shaders are able to read and write randomly from video memory and perform some basic mathematical and logical calculations.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] These SIMD processors were used to perform general calculations such as rendering polygons and signal processing.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] In recent GPU generations, the pixel shaders now are able to function as MIMD processors (now able to independently branch) utilizing up to 1 GB of texture memory with floating point formats.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] With such power, virtually any algorithm with steps that can be performed in parallel, such as volume ray casting or tomographic reconstruction, can be performed with tremendous acceleration.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The programmable pixel shaders can be used to simulate variations in the characteristics of lighting, shadow, reflection, emissive color and so forth.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Such simulations can be written using high level shading languages.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The primary goal of optimization is to skip as much of the volume as possible.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] A typical medical data set can be 1 GB in size.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] To render that at 30 frame/s requires an extremely fast memory bus.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Skipping voxels means less information needs to be processed.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Often, a volume rendering system will have a system for identifying regions of the volume containing no visible material.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This information can be used to avoid rendering these transparent regions.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This is a technique used when the volume is rendered in front to back order.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] For a ray through a pixel, once sufficient dense material has been encountered, further samples will make no significant contribution to the pixel and so may be neglected.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The use of hierarchical structures such as octree and BSP-tree could be very helpful for both compression of volume data and speed optimization of volumetric ray casting process.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Image segmentation is a manual or automatic procedure that can be used to section out large portions of the volume that one considers uninteresting before rendering, the amount of calculations that have to be made by ray casting or texture blending can be significantly reduced.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This reduction can be as much as from O(n) to O(log n) for n sequentially indexed voxels.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation also has significant performance benefits for other ray tracing algorithms.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Volume segmentation can subsequently be used to highlight or expose structures of interest.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] By representing less interesting regions of the volume in a coarser resolution, the data input overhead can be reduced.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] On closer observation, the data in these regions can be populated either by reading from memory or disk, or by interpolation.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The coarser resolution volume is resampled to a smaller size in the same way as a 2D mipmap image is created from the original.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] These smaller volume are also used by themselves while rotating the volume to a new orientation.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Pre-integrated volume rendering is a method that can reduce sampling artifacts by pre-computing much of the required data.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] It is especially useful in hardware-accelerated applications because it improves quality without a large performance impact.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Unlike most other optimizations, this does not skip voxels.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Rather it reduces the number of samples needed to accurately display a region of voxels.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] The idea is to render the intervals between the samples instead of the samples themselves.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] This technique captures rapidly changing material, for example the transition from muscle to bone with much less computation.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Image-based meshing is the automated process of creating computer models from 3D image data (such as MRI, CT, Industrial CT or microtomography) for computational analysis and design, e.g.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] For a complete display view, only one voxel per pixel (the front one) is required to be shown (although more can be used for smoothing the image), if animation is needed, the front voxels to be shown can be cached and their location relative to the camera can be recalculated as it moves.
[src:voxel-modeling/volume-rendering] Where display voxels become too far apart to cover all the pixels, new front voxels can be found by ray casting or similar, and where two voxels are in one pixel, the front one can be kept.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] In computing, a **voxel** is a representation of a value on a three-dimensional regular grid, akin to the two-dimensional pixel.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Voxels are frequently used in the visualization and analysis of medical and scientific data (e.g. geographic information systems (G.I.S.)).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Voxels also have technical and artistic applications in video games, largely originating with surface rendering in *Outcast* (1999).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] *Minecraft* (2011) makes use of an entirely voxelated world to allow for a fully destructible and constructable environment.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] **Voxel art**, of the sort used in *Minecraft* and elsewhere, is a style and format of 3D art analogous to pixel art.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] As with pixels in a 2D bitmap, voxels themselves do not typically have their position (i.e. coordinates) explicitly encoded with their values.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Instead, rendering systems infer the position of a voxel based upon its position relative to other voxels (i.e., its position in the data structure that makes up a single volumetric image).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Some volumetric displays use voxels to describe their resolution.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] For example, a cubic volumetric display might be able to show 512×512×512 (or about 134 million) voxels.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] In contrast to pixels and voxels, polygons are often explicitly represented by the coordinates of their vertices (as points).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] A direct consequence of this difference is that polygons can efficiently represent simple 3D structures with much empty or homogeneously filled space, while voxels excel at representing regularly sampled spaces that are non-homogeneously filled.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] This definition has the following advantage.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] If fixed voxel form is used within the whole model it is much easier to operate with voxel *nodal points* (i.e. three coordinates of this point).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Yet, there is the simple form of record: indexes of the elements in the model set (i.e. integer coordinates).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Model set elements in this case are *state parameters,* indicating voxel belonging to the modeled object or its separate parts, including their surfaces.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] The word *voxel* originated by analogy to "pixel", with *vo* representing "volume" (instead of pixel's "picture") and *el* representing "element"; a similar formation with *el* for "element" is the word "texel".
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] The term *hypervoxel* is a generalization of voxel for higher-dimensional spaces.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] A volume described as voxels can be visualized either by direct volume rendering or by the extraction of polygon iso-surfaces that follow the contours of given threshold values.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] The marching cubes algorithm(s) and Inertial frame of reference(s) are often used for iso-surface extraction, however other methods exist as well.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Both ray tracing and ray casting, as well as rasterisation, can be applied to voxel data to obtain 2D raster graphics to depict on a monitor.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Another technique for voxels involves raster graphics where one simply raytraces every pixel of the display into the scene, tracking an error term to determine when to step.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] A typical implementation will raytrace each pixel of the display starting at the bottom of the screen using what is known as a y-buffer.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] When a voxel is reached that has a higher y value on the display it is added to the y-buffer overriding the previous value and connected with the previous y-value on the screen interpolating the color values.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] There is a major downside to voxel rasterization when transformation is applied which causes severe aliasing.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] The advantage was the ability to rasterise using cheap integer calculations on a CPU without hardware acceleration.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] John Carmack also experimented with voxels for the *Quake III Arena* engine.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] One such problem cited by Carmack was the lack of graphics cards designed specifically for such rendering requiring them to be software rendered.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] A voxel represents a single sample, or data point, on a regularly spaced, three-dimensional grid.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] This data point can consist of a single datum, such as an opacity, or multiple data, such as a color in addition to opacity.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] A voxel represents only a single point on this grid, not a volume; the space between each voxel is not represented in a voxel-based data set.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Depending on the type of data and the intended use for the data set, this missing information may be reconstructed and/or approximated, e.g. via interpolation.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] The value of a voxel may represent various properties.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] In C.T. scans, the values are Hounsfield units, giving the opacity of material to X-rays.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Different types of value are acquired from M.R.I. or ultrasound.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Voxels can contain multiple scalar values, essentially vector (tensor) data; in the case of ultrasound scans with B-mode and Doppler data, density, and volumetric flow rate are captured as separate channels of data relating to the same voxel positions.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] While voxels provide the benefit of precision and depth of reality, they are typically large data sets and are unwieldy to manage given the bandwidth of common computers.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] However, through efficient compression and manipulation of large data files, interactive visualization can be enabled on consumer market computers.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Other values may be useful for immediate 3D rendering, such as a surface normal vector and color.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Technologies to extend voxels into four and five dimensions of data are under investigation.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Uses of voxels include volumetric imaging in medicine and representation of terrain in games and simulations.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Voxel terrain is used instead of a heightmap because of its ability to represent overhangs, caves, arches, and other 3D terrain features.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] These concave features cannot be represented in a heightmap due to only the top 'layer' of data being represented, leaving everything below it filled (the volume that would otherwise be the inside of the caves, or the underside of arches or overhangs).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] While scientific volume visualization does not require modifying the actual voxel data, voxel editors can be used to create art (especially 3D pixel art) and models for voxel-based games.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Some editors are focused on a single approach to voxel editing while others mix various approaches.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] There are a few voxel editors available that are not tied to specific games or engines.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] They can be used as alternatives or complements to traditional 3D vector modeling.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] A generalization of a voxel is the *toxel*, or temporal voxel.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] This is used in the case of a 4D data set, such as an image sequence that represents 3D space together with another spatial dimension or a time dimension.
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] In this way, an image could contain 100×100×100×100 voxels, which could be seen as a series of 100 frames of a 100×100×100 volume image (the equivalent for a 3D image would be showing a 2D cross-section of the image in each frame).
[src:voxel-modeling/voxel] Although storage and manipulation of such data requires large amounts of memory, it allows the representation and analysis of spacetime systems.
